    <section id="home">
        <header>
            <h1>Social Media's Effect on Teen Well-being</h1>
        </header>
    </section>
    <hr>
    <br>
    <br>
    <section id="introduction">
        <p>Social media use among teenagers is widespread, with many spending hours scrolling
            through platforms like TikTok, Instagram, and X (formerly Twitter). Concerns have grown over
            the potential negative impacts of prolonged social media use on young people’s mental health
            and well-being. While some studies highlight the positive aspects of social media, such as
            fostering connections, others point to risks lke social stigma, anxiety, and low self-esteem.
            The data collected was from two different sources, one of which was from Generation Survey
            and the other was from Pew Research Center. The data gathered from Generation Survey was
            available through their website. It is a large survey conducted in 2024 to explore the impact of
            social media use on the well-being of young people that targeted 3,785 Year 10 students
            across 340 Australian schools.
            The data gathered from Pew Research Center was available online. The sample consisted of
            1,316 U.S. teens aged 13 to 17, along with one parent from each teen’s household in 2022.</p>
    </section>

<img src="https://github.com/TheGuest1996/SchoolWebsiteDesign/blob/main/go%20down%20animation%20.gif?raw=true" class="center">

